New Order of the Near East
President Bush, Palestinian Prime Minister Abbas (not Mazen) and Israeli Prime Minister Sharon want to meet.
Is the United States serious about the peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into America's Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the policy planning staff at the US State Department, explains his "Roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What was achieved in Iraq – and what above all the Iraqi people can now stand up with the help of the Americans – will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented and peaceful Iraq could spur reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
It will take time until far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the Middle East have been implemented.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security policy, as well as economic and political aspects.
Thanks to the prior planning of the Americans and the entire world, and thanks to the rapid, concentrated, and targeted intervention of coalition troops during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less severe than assumed.
Here and there, there is a need for humanitarian aid, but fortunately, the massive crisis that was announced never materialized.
There are relatively few refugees and internally displaced persons within Iraq. In most cases, food, water, and medicine supplies are adequate or at least improving.
The Americas government has made approximately 600 million dollars available through the UN and non-governmental organizations for immediate humanitarian aid.
Furthermore, we must restore the basic order in Iraq.
Security is the indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without security, people cannot rebuild their country, return to work or school.
After Saddam's fall, there was a wave of looting, lawlessness, and settling of scores.
Now it is of utmost priority to bring this violence to an end.
In addition, it must be the task of international forces to ensure and eliminate all weapons of mass destruction, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbors further exacerbate the already volatile situation.
In the long term, we must help the Iraqis rebuild their police and military structures, so that they can secure their own safety without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be viewed more precisely as economic revitalization.
Physical capital is in better condition than expected, and the modern Iraq possesses a large reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, Iraq has a vast amount of raw materials to process.
The US is providing more than $2 billion in support for the initial reconstruction efforts.
Oil production is expected to be increased to a better level.
To the long-term challenges belong an increase in oil production and the repayment of Iraq's enormous debts.
The UN Security Council's decision to lift all sanctions is very welcome in this context.
Given the context and summaries provided, the translation of the German sentence into English is:
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The goal of the Americans - an intact Iraq where the law is respected and the government comes to power democratically - is not a fantasy, especially not because Iraq possesses a well-educated population and a relatively large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue on the current course and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be utilized.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have an impact on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly any foreign policy issue that occupies and polarizes public opinion more strongly than the Palestinian question.
Almost a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the US developed a plan that brings us closer to this goal in stages.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent an important step in this direction.
Now Palestinians and Israelis must be encouraged to initiate this process and take measures to improve the situation, so that they can then tackle more far-reaching issues at the negotiating table.
It cannot be allowed for terrorists to sabotage the peace process forever.
But solving the Palestinian issue is not automatically the solution to all problems of the Middle East.
Clearly and unequivocally, the challenges posed by Iran are evident. This country is developing weapons of mass destruction and has supported terrorism.
Such behavior disregards the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues on this path, it will have consequences.
When one turns away from terrorism and the construction of catastrophic weapons, the US is ready to re-establish good relations with this country.
Just as the US is ready to engage with Syria, if substantial attitude changes are made there.
A rather general issue is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
For too long, the United States tolerated the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to intervene and establish a representative form of government.
We have painfully felt the consequences of closed political systems leading to resentment and extremism against the interests of the US, the West, and the world at large.
That is why we support democracy and political reforms through the Middle East Partnership Initiative launched by Secretary of State Colin Powell in December 2002.
Closed economic systems also pose a threat.
As revealed in the previous year's "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the Development Status of Arab Countries), the Arab countries in the Middle East have fallen significantly behind other regions in the areas of personal freedom, women's rights, and economic and social development.
For too long, these countries have had to watch as economic growth passed them by.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
Would implementing his recently proposed plan for a free trade zone between the US and the Middle East within a decade be a viable foundation for such development.
